    q: "Is Colombian coffee good?",
    a: "Colombian coffee is consistently good across a wider range of price points than almost any other origin. The growing conditions (high altitude, two annual harvests, established infrastructure) allow Colombian producers to reliably hit the flavor profile the origin is known for: balanced sweetness, mild to medium acidity, and chocolate or caramel with clean fruit. At the specialty level (single-farm or cooperative lots from Huila, Nariño, or Tolima), Colombian coffee is exceptional. The challenge is distinguishing genuine specialty Colombian from commodity Colombian that shares the origin label without the quality."
  },
  {
    q: "What is the best region for Colombian coffee?",
    a: "Huila and Nariño produce the most celebrated specialty Colombian. Huila, in the southwestern highlands, is prized for full-bodied cups with dark chocolate, red fruit, and caramel. Nariño, at some of the highest altitudes in Colombian coffee growing (up to 2,200 MASL), produces bright, complex cups with citrus acidity and deep sweetness. Antioquia is the most consistent and benchmark-representative, while Tolima and Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta offer distinctive cups for buyers who want to explore beyond the flagship regions."
  },
  {
    q: "Why does Colombian coffee taste different from roaster to roaster?",
    a: "Several variables stack on top of origin. Region and specific farm or cooperative matter: Nariño coffee tastes different from Antioquia coffee even though both are labeled Colombian. Processing method matters: a washed Colombian runs bright and clean while a natural or honey-processed Colombian from the same farm tastes fruitier and heavier. Roast level is the most visible variable: a light-roasted Huila will taste completely different from a dark-roasted Colombian blend even if they started from similar beans. Buy from roasters who list region, processing method, and roast date. More information on the label means more transparency about what you are actually getting."
  },
  {
    q: "Is Huila better than Antioquia?",
    a: "Neither is objectively better, but they serve different preferences. Huila typically produces more complex, full-bodied cups with darker chocolate notes and red-fruit acidity. It is a richer, more structured cup that rewards specialty buyers looking for depth. Antioquia is the benchmark Colombian: reliable, balanced, caramel-forward, accessible. If you are introducing someone to Colombian coffee, Antioquia is more reliably consistent. If you want to drink the most celebrated specialty expressions of the origin, Huila has the best track record at auction and in specialty competition."
  },
  {
    q: "What is the best roast level for Colombian coffee?",
    a: "Light to medium roast is the answer for specialty Colombian, particularly from Huila or Nariño. Light roasting preserves the origin character: the specific acidity, fruit notes, and sweetness that distinguishes a great Colombian from generic coffee. Darker roasting pushes toward generic roast flavors (dark chocolate, char, bitterness) that mask origin character and make a Nariño indistinguishable from any other dark-roasted coffee. If you are drinking Colombian from a specialty roaster who has paid for quality lots, a light or medium roast is the only reason to pay for them."
  },
